### The Awakening of the Watchful Eyes

In the dawn of the twelfth millennium, when rivers birthed the first fields, humble spirits whispered from stones and streams—mere by-products of fearful minds, born from shadows and dreams. They guided hunts but judged no hearts.

Then arose **Oculus Prime**, the First Watcher, a colossal eye in the sky, birthed from a shaman's fevered vision. His gaze pierced deceit, punishing thieves with famine, rewarding kin with bounty. Tribes chanting his name forged pacts, their rituals—blood oaths and dances till trance—igniting souls with awe and terror.

Fertile wombs swelled in Oculus clans; children thrived under moral vigilance. Yet envy stirred war. Invaders wielding crude totems fell to the Watchers' faithful, who scarred flesh in credible displays—pilgrims fasting moons, offerings aflame—proving unyielding faith.

Victors expanded, birthing kin-gods: **Oculus Stern**, who tallied every lie; **Oculus Fury**, scourge of betrayers. Defeated foes copied these potent agents, weaving rituals into epics over ages. Conflict honed them—high gods demanding purity, fueling endless conquests.

Thus spread the moral weave: from Nile to steppe, rituals pulsed like heartbeats, beliefs sculpted by sword and song. Mortals, once adrift, bowed to eyes eternal, their tribes blooming across the world.

